Background Research¶

Objective¶

Use a supervised classification machine learning model to predict the likelihood of credit card default for customers of the Bank

Credit Card Default Explanation¶

The dataset was collected from a credit card provider.

Credit is the ability of the consumer to purchase goods and services prior to payment with the faith that payment will be made in the future.

Each consumer has their own Creditworthiness, which is usually measured by Credit Score, is a measure of the consumer's ability to pay back the credit they have borrowed. Consumer's with a higher Credit Score are less likely to default and will usually be given a higher credit limit.

Factors used in predicting default¶

Some factors that affect a consumer's Credit Score include:

  • Payment History => Lenders usually base the amount of risk on whether consumers have past credit accounts on time
  • Amounts Owed => Outstanding Balance
  • New Credit => Lenders dislike consumers that open new credit accounts in a short perio of time
  • Length of Credit History => Lenders prefer Credit Accounts that are established for a longer time
  • Credit Mix => Lenders like to see a healthy mix of credit such as Mortgages, Installment Loans and Retail Accounts etc.

Pearon's r Correlation¶

To check the correlation between the different numerical features, we will use Pearson's r correlation. The Pearson's r correlation is able to measure linear correlation between two variables.

Formula: $\begin{equation} \rho = \frac{COV(X,Y)}{\sigma_X\sigma_Y} \end{equation}$

Dealing with imbalanced datasets¶

As seen previously, our dataset is imblanaced with 1260 records of customers not defaulting and only 340 records of customers defaulting.

We can deal with our imbalanced dataset during different steps of the ML Workflow:

  • During Data Preprocessing
    1. Oversampling
    2. Undersampling
  • Using Evaluation Metrics
    • Using Balanced Accuracy inplace of Accuracy
  • Using a different Model
    • Try using a different perspective like using Anomaly Detection algorithms instead of a supervised learning approach
    • Using Penalized classification to impose an additional cost on the model for making mistakes on the minority class during training

Note the list only includes methods that are more common. There exist a lot of other techniques to deal with imbalanced dataset

References:

  • https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/463224/which-performance-metrics-for-highly-imbalanced-multiclass-dataset

Oversampling vs Undersampling:

Fig 1: Undersampling vs Oversampling


Despite the advantage of balancing classes through resampling, these techniques also have their weaknesses.

One of the basic ways to perform oversampling is to duplicate random records from the minority class but this approach may lead to overfitting issues by creating redundant samples.

In undersampling, the simplest technique involves randomly discarding records from the majority class but this can result in a loss of information that may be necessary to train the model accurately


In this case, we will be using SMOTE (or more specifically SMOTE-NC which is a variant of SMOTE designed specifically for datasets with nominal and continuous features). SMOTE is a more sophisticated resampling technique whereby instead of just randomly duplicating existing records from the minority class, it would:

  1. Randomly pick a record from the minority class
  2. Compute the k-nearest neighbours for this point
  3. Choose one of the neighbours and place a synthetic point anywhere on the line joining the point and its chosen neighbour
In [ ]:
# https://imbalanced-learn.org/dev/references/generated/imblearn.over_sampling.SMOTENC.html
# Obtain a list of categorical columns
categorical_features = X_train.select_dtypes(include=['category']).columns
# Obtain column index for categorical columns
categorical_features_idx = [X_train.columns.get_loc(col) for col in categorical_features]
# Instantiate SMOTENC
sm = SMOTENC(random_state=random_state, categorical_features=categorical_features_idx)
X_res, y_res = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

Notice that SMOTE-NC was only used to resample data from the training set (X_test=>X_res and y_test=>y_res).

A common mistake is to actually resample the entire dataset before splitting. However, it is imporant to only perform oversampling on the training set only in order to ensure that the model learns to generalise to new unseen data that may have imbalanced class distribution instead of overfitting to the oversampled data

Categorical Encoding¶

As our dataset contains categorical data and many machine learning models can only work with numerical values, it is necessary to transform the categorical values of relevant features into numerical ones. This process is known as encoding and there are several ways to encode our data:

  1. One Hot Encoder
  2. Label Encoder
  3. Ordinal Encoder

We will be using One Hot Encoder for our categorical features that are nominal such as Gender and Marraige Status while we will be using Ordinal Encoder for our categorical features that are Ordinal such as Education and AgeBin

Feature Scaling¶

Feature Scaling is the process of scaling numerical features within the dataset to a similar scale.

Certain Machine Learning Algorithms such as Gradient Descent Based Algorithms (e.g. Logistic Regression, Ridge Classifier, Perceptron) and Distance Based Algorithms (e.g. KNNClassifier and SVC) are more sensitive to feature scaling and requires the data to be scaled.

On the other hand, Tree Based Algorithms (e.g. RandomForest, GradientBoosting) are more insensitive to the scale of the features since trees only split a node based on a single feature. This means that other features do not influence this split which explains why different features can be of different scales

There are two popular ways to perform Feature Scaling:

  1. Normaliation
  2. Standardization

Normalization

Normalization also known as Min-Max scaling, is a scaling technique in which values are shifted and rescaled so that they end up ranging between 0 and 1.

In SKLearn, Normalization can be implemented using MinMaxScaler

Formula:

$\begin{equation} X' = \frac{X - X_{min}}{X_{max} - X_{min}} \end{equation}$

Standardization

Standardization is another scaling method where values are centered around the mean with a unit standard deviation. This means that the mean of the feautre becomes zero and the distribution of the scaled feature has a unit standard deviation (or a standard deviation of 1).

In SKlearn, Standardization can be implemented using StandardScaler

Formula:

$\begin{equation} X' = \frac{X - \mu}{\sigma} \end{equation}$

Standardization vs Normalization

Standardization Normalization
Less Sensitive to outliers Sensitive to outliers
Centers data around the mean and scales to a standard deviation of 1 Rescales values to a range between 0 and 1
Preserves the relationship between data points May not preserve the relationship between the data points
Changes the shape of the original distribution Retains the shape of the original distribution

Notice how previously from our EDA, we identified that Bill and Pay contained quite a lot of outliers. Since Standardization is less sensitive to outliers compared to Normalization, it is more likely that scaling our features using Standardization can help improve the performance of our model

4. Model Selection¶

In order to select a model for hyperparameter tuning, we will run the preprocessed data through some models and deem the best model based on the evaluation metrics to be chosen later

Pipeline¶

First, we will use a pipeline to preprocess the data (the same way as done in part 3) since a pipeline can help:

  1. Improve ML Workflow
  2. Prevent Data Leakage from the Train subset into the Test subset

Since we are using SMOTE-NC for oversampling, we have to use the ImbalancedLearn pipeline instead of the SKLearn pipeline so that we can implement SMOTE-NC within each cross-validation fold instead of implementing it outside of the CV (which will result in Data Leakage)

In [ ]:
# Creating Steps for Pipeline

# Function to log scale data
def log_scale(X):
    df = pd.DataFrame(X.reset_index(drop=True))
    # np.log1p() applies log(1+x) to all elements of the column
    df[['Age']] = np.log1p(df[['Age']])
    return df

# Function to discretize age
def discretize(X):
    df = pd.DataFrame(X.reset_index(drop=True))
    
    kbins = KBinsDiscretizer(n_bins=9, strategy='kmeans', encode='ordinal')

    # Reshape since kbins require a 2d array as input
    age_bin = kbins.fit_transform(np.array(df['Age']).reshape(-1,1))
    age_bin = pd.Series(age_bin.flatten(), name='AgeBin', dtype='category')

    # Concatenate age_bin at idx
    idx = df.columns.get_loc('Age') + 1
    # Use idx-1 since we no longer need Age as a column since we have ageBin
    return pd.concat((df.iloc[:, :idx-1], age_bin, df.iloc[:, idx:]), axis=1)  

# Transformer for categorical columns
categoricalTransformer = ColumnTransformer(
    [
        ('oneHotEncode', OneHotEncoder(categories='auto', sparse=False), ['Gender', 'Marriage_Status']),
        ('ordinalEncodeEducation', OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['high school', 'university', 'post-graduate']], handle_unknown="use_encoded_value", unknown_value=-1), ['Education']),
        ('ordinalEncodeAgeBin', OrdinalEncoder(categories='auto', handle_unknown='use_encoded_value', unknown_value=-1), ['AgeBin'])
    ],
    remainder="passthrough"
)

# Define numeric columns
numeric_cols = ['Credit_Limit', 'Bill1', 'Bill2', 'Bill3', 'Pay1', 'Pay2', 'Pay3']

# Transformer for numeric columns
numericTransformer = ColumnTransformer(
    [
        ('scaling', StandardScaler(), numeric_cols),
    ],
    remainder="passthrough"
)

# Combine the two transformers into preprocessor
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    [
        ("categorical", categoricalTransformer, ['Gender', 'Education', 'Marriage_Status', 'AgeBin']),
        ("numeric", numericTransformer, numeric_cols)
    ],
    remainder="passthrough"
)

steps = [
    ('overSampling', SMOTENC(random_state=random_state, categorical_features=[X_train.columns.get_loc(col) for col in (X_train.select_dtypes(include=['category']).columns)])),
    ('discretization', FunctionTransformer(discretize)),
    ('preprocessor', preprocessor),
    ('model')
]

model_step = len(steps) - 1

Evaluation Metrics¶

Confusion Matrix:

Recall

Recall is used when we want the model to spot as many real 1s as possible

Formula: $\begin{equation} Recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN} \nonumber \end{equation}$


Precision

Precision is used when we want the prediction of 1 to be as correct as possible

Formula: $\begin{equation} Precision = \frac{TP}{TP + FP} \nonumber \end{equation}$


Accuracy

Accuracy is used when we are interested in predicting both 0 and 1 correctly and our dataset is balanced enough

Formula: $\begin{equation} Accuracy = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + FN + FP + TN} \nonumber \end{equation}$

Balanced Accuracy

Balanced Accuracy is defined as the average of recall obtained on each class and is used to deal with imbalanced datasets

Formula: $\begin{equation} Balanced Accuracy = \frac{1}{2}(\frac{TP}{TP + FN} + \frac{TN}{TN + FP}) \nonumber \end{equation}$

F1 Score

F1 is a popular measure for imbalanced dataset and is defined as the harmonic mean between Precision and Recall

Formula: $\begin{equation} F1 = \frac{2 \cdot Precision \cdot Recall}{Precision+Recall} \nonumber \end{equation}$

FBeta

In the F1 measure, both recall are equally balanced. The Fbeta-measure is an abstraction of the F-score where the balance of precision and recall in the calculation is controlled by a coefficient called beta. The common weights of beta are:

  • F0.5 Score (beta=0.5): More weight on precision, less weight on recall
  • F1 Score (beta=1): Balance the weight on precision and recall
  • F2 Score (beta=2): More weight on recall, less weight on precision

Formula: $\begin{equation} F_\beta = \frac{(1 + \beta^2) \cdot (Precision \cdot Recall)}{(\beta^2 \cdot precision) + recall} \nonumber \end{equation}$

Since the main goal for the financial company is to identify the customers that are likely to default, it is more important to capture as many default cases as possible (i.e. positive cases). However, using recall as an evaluation metric alone is not wise (since a model that does "print(1)" would also have a recall of 1.0).

Hence, it seems better to prioritise recall over precision by using FBeta with beta = 2

As such, we will be using:

  • Balanced Accuracy
  • FBeta (Beta=2)
  • ROC AUC

as our evaluation metrics to try and evaluate our models

Since Scikit learn doesn't have f2 score as one of its metrics under sklearn.metrics.get_scorer_names() (this contains all the metrics which can be used for cross_validate and GridSearchCV). As such, we can define our own f2 scorer by using the make_scorer function to create a scorer object

In [ ]:
# Make custom f2 score (https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html#scoring-parameter)
ftwo = make_scorer(fbeta_score, beta=2)
evaluation_metrics = {
    "balanced_accuracy": "balanced_accuracy",
    "f2": ftwo,
    "ROC_AUC" : "roc_auc"
}

def plot_learning_curve(
    model,
    X,
    y,
    scoring,
    cv=StratifiedKFold(shuffle=True, random_state=random_state),
    train_sizes=np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 10),
    ax=None,
):
    try:
        model_name = type(model[-1].regressor).__name__
    except:
        try:
            model_name = type(model[-1]).__name__
        except:
            model_name = type(model).__name__
    if ax is None:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores, fit_times, _ = learning_curve(
        model,
        X,
        y,
        cv=cv,
        n_jobs=-1,
        train_sizes=train_sizes,
        return_times=True,
        scoring=scoring,
    )
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)

    ax.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, "o-", color="r", label="Training score")
    ax.plot(
        train_sizes, test_scores_mean, "o-", color="g", label="Cross-validation score"
    )
    ax.legend(loc="best")
    ax.set(
        ylim=(
            min(np.nanmin(train_scores), np.nanmin(test_scores)) - 0.1,
            1.0,
        )
    )
    ax.set_title(f"Learning Curve of {model_name}")
    ax.set_ylabel(f"{scoring}")
    ax.set_xlabel("Train Sizes")
    return ax

Models Explained ¶
  1. Decision Tree

A decision tree is the simplest of all tree-based model. The base of the tree is the root node and from the root node flows a series of decision nodes. Each decision node can then be split into further sub-nodes. Nodes that no longer split are called leaf or terminal nodes. The main contributor affecting the decision tree's accuracy is how each decision node is split

  1. Random Forest

In Random Forest, bagging is used to generate multiple training sets with replacement (i.e. the initial dataset is divided into multiple datasets using randomized sampling). Then a single decision tree is built on each sample before the resultant prediction is combined using either voting or averaging in parallel

  1. Gradient Boosting

Gradient Boosting is similar to Random Forest in that it is also made up of an ensemble of Decision Trees. However, instead of using a single tree to build on each sample, each new tree is built to improve on the deficiencies of the previous tree (also known as boosting). This is done by minimising the loss function as the algorithm builds each tree

  1. Ada Boost

AdaBoost, also called Adaptive Boost, is like Gradient Boosting since it also combines a number of weak trees to form a stronger tree. However, AdaBoost was designed for a specific loss function (exponential loss function) while Gradient Boosting is a more generic algorithm that can use any differentiable loss function

  1. Logistic Regression

Logistic Regression is one of the most simple model for binary classification problems. It fits a sigmoid function

$\begin{equation} S(x) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-x}} \nonumber \end{equation}$

to estimate the probability of an event occuring. A threshold is then set (usually 0.5) which will then predict the class based on the probability

e.g. S(x) >= 0.5 is class 1 while S(x) < 0.5 is class 0

  1. Perceptron

A perceptron is a single neural network unit that contains weight and biases. It uses an activation function to map the input features to an output and in the case of Binary Classification, this activation function is usually the same Sigmoid function used for logistic regression

  1. KNN Classifier

In KNN Classifier, the class is predicted based on a vote from its nearest neighbours. The value for n neighbours should be an odd number to try and prevent a tie of vote.

e.g. If the record has 3 neighbours of in the positive class and 2 neighbours of in the negative class, then the record will be predicted as part of the positive class

  1. Gaussian NB

Gaussian Naive Bayes is a classification technique that based on the probabilistic approach and Gaussian distribution. It is an extension of naive Bayes with the assumption that each feature is independent

$\begin{equation} P(A|B) = \frac{P(B|A)P(A)}{P(B)} \nonumber \end{equation}$

Observations:

  • Gaussian Naive Bayes seems to have the best performance. This is likely because the features are all highly independent (which is indicated by the low correlation in the correlation matrix)
  • In general, it seems that gradient descent based models perform better than tree based models. As seen in the learning curve for Random Forest Classifier and Decision Tree Classifier, it seems very likely that there is overfitting in the tree based models
  • Since logistic regression and naive bayes seem to perform better, the relationship between the different features within the dataset might actually be simple. These models which assume linear relationships are more effective in capturing the simpler relationships present in the data. On the other hand, more complex models like tree-based models might struggle to capture these relationships due to their tendency to overfit when faced with simpler patterns.

Therefore, we will be selecting two models for hyperparameter tuning. They are:

  • Gaussian Naive Bayes (since it has the best performance for f2 score)
  • Logistic Regression (since it has the best performance for balanced accuracy and ROC AUC)
  • AdaBoost (since it is an ensemble model, it might be able to perform better after tuning)

Observations

Since we want our model to accurately predict as many defaulters as possible, we want our True Postive Count to be as high as possible and our False Negative Count to be as low as possible.

From the confusion matrix, it seems that Gaussian Naive Bayes seems to be able to do this quite well with a very low False Negative Count of 17 and a very high True Positive Count of 255.

Although, Gaussian Naive Bayes has a very high False Postive Count of 869, it doesn't matter as much since our main goal is to build a model that can accurately predict customers who are going to default, it's better to have more false alarms that can be filtered out by the bank than for the model to miss an actual customer who will default

Hyperparameter Tuning and Evaluation

We will be using GridSearchCV to run through the parameters and see which model's parameter will give the best recall

Hyperparameters to be tuned

  • Naive Bayes:

    • var_smoothing => the portion of the largest variance of all features that is added to variances for calculation stability

  • Logistic Regression:

    • penalty => type of regularization to be used either l1 (lasso), l2 (ridge), elasticnet (combination of both l1 and l2) or none
    • solver => algorithm used in the optimization problem
    • C => The inverse of regularization strength. Smaller values specify stronger regularization

  • AdaBoost

    • algorithm => type of algorithm to be used (either real boosting algorithm or discrete boosting algorithm)
    • n_estimators => the number of estimators at which boosting is terminated
    • learning_rate => Weight applied to each classifier at each boosting iteration. A higher learning rate would increase the contribution of each classifier

    "var_smoothing": np.logspace(-10, 0, 100),

Feature Importance

Although Gaussian Naive Bayes is our best performing model, Naive Bayes works by determining the conditional and unconditional probabilities associated with the features. Thus, there are no coefficients computed or associated with the features used to train the model. As such, we will be extracting the most important features from another model. In this case I will be using Logistic Regression

In [ ]:
# Show the feature importance for AdaBoost

# Get feature importance of tuned adaBoost
importance = tuned_logisticRegression_clf.named_steps["model"].coef_[0]
# Get the feature names
feature_names = ['Gender_Female', 'Gender_Male', 'MarriageStatus_Married', 'MarriageStatus_Single', 'Education', 'AgeBin', 'Credit_Limit', 'Bill1', 'Bill2', 'Bill3', 'Pay1', 'Pay2', 'Pay3']

# Convert to dataframe
importance_series = pd.Series(importance, index=feature_names).sort_values(ascending=False)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 9))
sns.barplot(
    x=importance_series, y=importance_series.index, ax=ax
)
ax.set_title("Feature Importance of Tuned Logistic Regression")
# Set text labels
[ax.text(x=val, y=idx, s=round(val, 6)) for idx, val in zip(np.arange(0,len(importance_series)), importance_series.values)]

plt.show()

In Logistic Regression, the coefficients are log-odds (so exponentiating them converts them to odds). A negative coefficient has odds < 1 implying that the odds of the event occuring is lower than the baseline while a positive coefficient has odds > 1 implying that there is an increased odd of the event occuring relative to baseline

Observation:

  • Since Pay1, Pay2 and Pay3 all have negative coefficients, it suggests that for every one unit increase in pay, the odds of defaulting decreases (since those who paying more suggest they are not in any financial trouble and will end up not defaulting).
  • On the other hand, since Bill1, Bill2 and Bill3 all have positive coefficients, it suggests that for every one unit increase in bill, the odds of defaulting increases (since there is a higher chance a customer will not be able to pay a higher bill)
  • Females have a slightly higher odds ($e^{0.000283} \approx$ 1.000283) of defaulting compared to males ($e^{-0.000285} \approx$ 0.999715)
  • Those who are single have a lower odd ($e^{-0.00039} \approx$ 0.999610) of defaulting compared to those that are married ($e^{0.000387} \approx$ 1.000387)
  • With a positive coefficient for AgeBin and a negative coefficient for education, it seems that those who are older people are more likely to default while to those with a higher educational background are less likely to default
